Going for a photography drive, taking photos of our local American Kestrels I noticed an odd looking bird in the bunch that seemed "not as welcome" as the normal group.  Once home, I looked closer at the "odd man out" and after doing some searching I saw it was most likely a Merlin.  I am in contact with Matthew at the American Kestrel Fund and he mentioned that I should contact Cornell as for South Central PA in February, this would be quite rare, but he also agreed that he thought it was a Merlin.  It seems he is taking up temporary residence with the local Kestrels.

TRIP COMMENTS: I walk this area several times a week.  Leggetts Creek North Scranton has a 3 level echo system. The bottom ATV trail runs along side the creek.  The second level comprised of various bush and Staghorn Suma type shrubs..  The upper top path has a lot of high grass with various trees spread sparingly throughout and several paths that interconnect.  The walk basically starts behind one baseball field and ends at another.  It's not very long, about a 15 minute walk from one end to the other.  You can spend hours cutting up and down to the different levels (as I often do).  Because of the various echo systems, the bird life is very diverse.  At the creek level you'll find Kingfishers, ducks, herons, and just about any other water fowl you can think of depending on the time of year.  Lots of woodpeckers all types.  The middle level you'll have Robins, Bluebirds, Phoebes and the like.  While the upper level is perfect for warbler type birds and many others.  Every raptor bird known loves this place.  Great little hot spot.

SPECIES COMMENTS: Merlin – Feb. 22, 2022--Looked for a Merlin on my way into town on the former Louden Hill farm property – now owned by Delaware Quarries.  Memories of seeing one here on Jan. 4, 2019 and again on Dec. 23, 2021 loomed in my mind. And on my return trip, it was there perched on a telephone wire with its back towards me!  Only an estimated 3 million in the world and this same one, probably, is still here this winter from my December observation.  Larger than a Kestrel, smaller than a SSHA – it was about 150 ft from RT 29 – it has a very dark brown back, wings and tail – it must be a female.  Head looked roundish and its tail roundish and not long like a SSHA.  I took my eyes off the road to look to the right to see a better view of it and discovered I had driven to the left of the yellow line by more than 1 foot!  Fortunately there were not any cars coming.  I wouldn’t have looked to see the bird when I was closest to it, if there were.  Still it brought home to me that it only takes a second or two to end up where you don’t want to be.  Only for a Merlin.  Jerry Skinner said to me back in 2019 that “maybe it will stay here for the winter.”  I think this could be the fourth winter this female has used this area.

TRIP COMMENTS: General: Unplanned, impulse visit since we were in the neighborhood. Our first time here in since the Audubon CBC in 2016, back when the paved path to the wastewater treatment plant was new. The park had gone through some other changes since then, most notably the loss of some trees on the west end. Mid-afternoon bird activity level on a day of unimpressive migration was, understandably, not high. --Route: Walked through the scrubby western end of the park, looping up past the pond to meet the newish paved SRT connector trail, walk out to the wastewater treatment plant, then head back toward the parking lot, eventually getting off the pavement and waking through the mulch pile area. 1.72 miles recorded by app, including a bit of backtracking.--Weather: High 60s F, sunny, minimal wind, cloudless blue sky.
SPECIES COMMENTS: A little late.  Small, dark, streaky falcon shot through the mulch pile area. Dull brown/gray-colored upper parts, no hint of kestrel orange hues in plumage. Barred undertail, distinctively shaped falcon wings. Did not get a look at its face.

SPECIES COMMENTS: Studied for good while (never saw it fly off), sitting in tree at top of 5th Tee hill.  Brown vertical lines all over chest, not from neck down...not heavy and dark, noted what looked like line thru eye ...white over the back of eye made it look line line thru eye, banded tail, small / medium size hawk / falcon. I had to rule out immature cooper / sharpie based on the head / face I saw.  ( Merlin has been seen at that park.)

TRIP COMMENTS: Darner sp. - 2----Another amazing flight, 299 raptors in just under 5 hours. Sunny, temps soaring to 81F, light SW wind. Conditions began mostly sunny with just a faint haze and scattered clouds. A high layer of patterned clouds arrived at 12:45, then darker cumulus around 2:30. The wind picked up and switched to W as a cold front approached at 3:45, with the front passing through around 4:30. The "Pennsburg Bubble" held true again, with storm cells to our north and south but hardly a drop here. The cell even re-formed after passing us.
SPECIES COMMENTS: 1:22, 2:04, 2:55.----Careful study on these birds against kestrel, looking for stiff wingbeats, very direct flight, and broader wing bases with proportionally shorter tail (not fanned). All passed through quickly at moderate to high altitude.

SPECIES COMMENTS: I was using the Merlin app to identify a call I’d never heard before. It consistently returned Merlin as the result. Then one flew out of a tall tree and landed on a lower branch (first sighting). Then I realized two were calling back and forth and found both. They flew several times and had very fast wingbeats. I got good looks at both of them and while the lighting was a bit tough, I saw brown striping on their undersides, yellowish tan leg feathers and dark backside. I believe I picked up a blueish hue on one backside. They both flew to and from a somewhat conical nest - did not see or hear chicks so I think they were building. A fish crow was swooping at one of the perched merlins which would cause the Merlin to fly at it.

Same mated pair of Merlins I saw yesterday, I have to assume, since I’m near their nest. Better lighting today and I confirmed the blue tint of one of their backs. One has a slightly darker brown head than the other. Today they were resting in a tall bare tree. Got good looks at their striped bellies and faces.

Survey with Malcolm Kurtz to confirm Merlin breeding status at Chatham University. Kurtz has monitored Merlins at location for months. We observed a family of 3 Merlins (male/female/juvenile)near Berry Hall. Juvenile distinguished from female by lack of feather wear and molt. Head, back, and wing coverts all uniformly brown. Adult Merlins molt body feathers May-Sept and female has molting feathers on crown. Adult female also shows considerable wear on rectrices. See photos.

SPECIES COMMENTS: Two adults hanging around pine grove in center of Somerset Golf Course. Small Falcons with blue-gray backs. Striped breast. Dark under tail with white bands. Chest-heavy with tapered appearance to tail more so than kestrel. In semi open forest on golf course with scattered pines. Seemed to be an adult pair. They were calling to each other with high pitched chatter,  faster sounding than a Kestrel. Audio clip captured one of the Merlins calling at the beginning of the clip in the background.  At the end of the audio clip, a golf shot is heard, followed by a groan. Bad cell phone images will show profile. Was golfing, but these birds were tame and close. One was along the entrance drive later.  This seemed like a pair interacting with each other on their breeding ground, or possibly reuniting on a wintering location after breeding elsewhere.  Known to be expanding their breeding range south.

Scott's Run lake hotspot.  ----Today I saw one of the worst things I've ever seen in nature:--Two chickadees seemingly stuck together and together caught on something, hanging upside down, very high up in an inaccessible tree....  They struggled and struggled and spun around like an upside-down top, feathers flying, desperately writhing and agitatedly vocaizing as other chickadees perched very nearby and those too called and called.  Then the two caught birds would exhaust themselves and stop struggling and just hang, always upside down, wings drooping.  It was so confusing and pathetic and non-sensical and horrible to watch, and there was nothing I could do for them - so I just cried.

TRIP COMMENTS: 42F up to 50F, partly Sunny, wind SW 15-20mph

Some activity over the water with equal numbers of Common and Red-throated Loons with the latter birds moving west.  A few scaup were westbound as well as White-winged Scoters and Bonaparte’s Gulls.  Despite the good number of Bonaparte’s, nothing unusual was with them.  Roger Donn assisted during the last part of the watch.
Very little activity.  Dump trucks and bulldozers continuously passed between me and the lake throughout the survey.
Very little waterbird movement.  Roger Donn assisted during the latter part of the count.
Much quieter on the lake today than yesterday, still a few westbound Lesser Scaup.
There was a light movement of westbound Lesser Scaup, but little else.  A couple of Caspian Terns were getting a bit on the late side.
Very little activity, though there was a little more waterfowl diversity.  Bernie O’Connor assisted with the count.

Waterbird count.  Despite the south wind and mild conditions, there were a few birds moving.  Highlight was a dark morph juvenile Parasitic Jaeger that flew off the lake to within a few hundred yards offshore to pursue Ring-billed Gulls, ignoring the smaller more common Bonaparte’s Gulls, for a couple of minutes before flying back out into the lake.  Joe Susi and Roger Donn assisted with the count.

TRIP COMMENTS: Property Big Sit year 4.  Total species count was 52.  Last year's count was 48 species.  Fairly productive but I was hoping for more given the favorable NW winds and the Birdcast migration indicating there would be a good nocturnal movement.  NFC results were underwhelming.  This was the coldest Big Sit I can remember, even in the afternoon I was only comfortable when I moved into the sun.  I had a nice variety of raptors but really struck out on warblers.----Seven new birds were added to the Big Sit bringing the cumulative total up to 75.  Also added one new mammal to the count.----New birds added to the count: Red-shouldered hawk, Peregrine falcon, Tree swallow, House wren, Gray catbird, Dark-eyed junco, Common yellowthroat----Weather: Partly cloudy to start but quickly clearing. 48F rising to 55F.  Winds NW at 3-10 mph. One shooting star.----Butterflies: Cabbage white 2, Monarch (2 - high and headed south)----Mammals: Eastern cottontail (new for the Big Sit), Eastern gray squirrel 2

SPECIES COMMENTS: I was in my goldenrod/shrub field that now contains about 15% open paths when I saw the Merlin fly by me about 18 ft away and low.  It was larger and stockier than a kestrel, 'weak' face pattern, definitely did not have the kestrel's double mustache.  It's tail wasn't as long as a sharp-shinned and it had a large rounded head as opposed to the sharpie's small head.  The 3 previous times I have seen one at the Delaware Quarry - which is only about 1/4 mile from my house as birds fly, they have each had a dark back and brown stripes - the colors of a female.  The bird today had a light blue gray head, back, wings and tail and its breast was white with light streaks - a male. The picture here is a good example of what it looked like. Lovely! -- https://www.allaboutbirds.org/guide/Merlin/overview
Mixing it up with one of the crows.
